A subsample of 40 g of the analytical pulp is digested with aqua-regia.  The resulting gold in solution is extracted into DIBK and quantified on a graphite furnace AAS.  Range to 150 ppb.

A subsample of up to 40 g of the analytical pulp is fused in a lead collection fire assay.  The resultant prill is digested in aqua-regia and the gold content of the sample determined by AAS (fire assay with AAS finish).

A subsample of 40 g of the analytical pulp is fused in a lead collection fire assay.  The resulting prill is digested in aqua-regia and the gold content of the sample is determined by graphite furnace AAS

A subsample of up to 40 g of the analytical pulp is fused in a lead collection fire assay.  The resultant prill is digested in aqua-regia and the gold content of the sample is determined by ICP-OES (fire assay with ICP-OES finish).

A subsample of 0.5 g of the analytical pulp is digested with aqua-regia and then bulked to volume with water.  The solution is presented to an ICPOES for quantification of the elements of interest.  Range is to 0.5% except Fe (10%), Mn (1%), Ag (100 ppm).
A nominal subsample of 0.2 g of the analytical pulp is digested using an HF/multi acid digest and the solution is presented to an ICPMS for the quantification of the elements of interest
AF = Alkali Fustion digest (100% Digest).  The sample is mixed with a flux and fused to form a glass bead which is then dissolved by acid digest.

A 0.1 g subsample of the analytical pulp is fused with lithium metaborate followed by dissolution to give a total solution.   The solution is presented to an ICPOES and an ICPMS for the determination of elements of interest (alkali fusion, dissolved in solution – total digest, ICP-OES and ICP-MS finish).

A multi-element suite of elements by ICP and is used where ore grade levels are present.  A modified aqua-regia /perchloric acid attack is used to dissolve the elements being analysed and the solution is presented to an ICP-OES for the elements of interest (modified aqua regia/perchloric digest, ICP-OES finish).
A  subsample is digested in aqua regia, and presented to an ICPMS for quantification of the elements of interest (aqua regia digest, ICP-MS finish).
XRF analysis by pressed powder (long count time for improved detection limits).  XRF determines total values and is suitable for the analysis of drill core, rocks, stream sediments and soils.
